In this exercise, we reduce to row-echelon form (REF) and then to reduced row-echelon form (RREF).  State the row operations that do this. 
<me>\begin{bmatrix}0 \amp 3 \amp -6 \amp 6 \amp 4 \amp -5 \\ 3 \amp -7 \amp 8 \amp -5 \amp 8 \amp 9 \\ 3 \amp -9 \amp 12 \amp -9 \amp 6 \amp 15 \end{bmatrix} \sim \begin{bmatrix}3 \amp -9 \amp 12 \amp -9 \amp 6 \amp 15 \\ 3 \amp -7 \amp 8 \amp -5 \amp 8 \amp 9 \\ 0 \amp 3 \amp -6 \amp 6 \amp 4 \amp -5 \end{bmatrix} \sim \begin{bmatrix}3 \amp -9 \amp 12 \amp -9 \amp 6 \amp 15 \\ 0 \amp 2 \amp -4 \amp 4 \amp 2 \amp -6 \\ 0 \amp 3 \amp -6 \amp 6 \amp 4 \amp -5 \end{bmatrix} </me>
Cover the top row and look at the remaining two rows for the left-most nonzero column.
<me>
  \begin{bmatrix}3 \amp -9 \amp 12 \amp -9 \amp 6 \amp 15 \\ 0 \amp 2 \amp -4 \amp 4 \amp 2 \amp -6 \\ 0 \amp 3 \amp -6 \amp 6 \amp 4 \amp -5 \end{bmatrix} \sim \begin{bmatrix}3 \amp -9 \amp 12 \amp -9 \amp 6 \amp 15 \\ 0 \amp 1 \amp -2 \amp 2 \amp 1 \amp -3 \\ 0 \amp 3 \amp -6 \amp 6 \amp 4 \amp -5 \end{bmatrix} \sim \begin{bmatrix}3 \amp -9 \amp 12 \amp -9 \amp 6 \amp 15 \\ 0 \amp 1 \amp -2 \amp 2 \amp 1 \amp -3 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp 4 \end{bmatrix}
</me>
<em>Final step to create the reduced row echelon form:</em> Beginning with the rightmost leading entry, and working upwards to the left, create zeros at each leading entry and scale rows to transform each leading entry into 1. 
<me>
  \begin{bmatrix}3 \amp -9 \amp 12 \amp -9 \amp 0 \amp -9 \\ 0 \amp 1 \amp -2 \amp 2 \amp 0 \amp -7 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp 4 \end{bmatrix} \sim \begin{bmatrix}3 \amp 0 \amp -6 \amp 9 \amp 0 \amp -72 \\ 0 \amp 1 \amp -2 \amp 2 \amp 0 \amp -7 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp 4 \end{bmatrix} \sim \begin{bmatrix}1 \amp 0 \amp -2 \amp 3 \amp 0 \amp -24 \\ 0 \amp 1 \amp -2 \amp 2 \amp 0 \amp -7 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp 4 \end{bmatrix}
</me>
  </p>
</li>

<li>
  <p>
Identify the pivot columns, the basic variables, and the free variables for the system:
<me> \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 6 \amp 0 \amp 3 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp -8 \amp 0 \amp 5 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp 7 \end{bmatrix}
</me> 
which can also be written as 
<md>
  <mrow> x_1 + 6x_2 + 3x_4 \amp \mathstrut = 0 </mrow>
  <mrow> x_3 - 8x_4 \amp \mathstrut = 5 </mrow>
  <mrow> x_5 \amp \mathstrut = 7 </mrow>
</md>
  </p>
</li>

<li>
  <p>
For the linear system
<md alignment="alignat" alignat-columns="5">
   <mrow> 0x_1 \amp +3x_2 \amp - 6x_3 \amp  + 6x_4 \amp + 4x_5 \amp = -5 </mrow>
   <mrow> 3x_1 \amp - 7x_2 \amp + 8x_3 \amp - 5x_4 \amp + 8x_5 \amp = 9 </mrow>
   <mrow> 3x_1 \amp - 9x_2 \amp + 12x_3 \amp - 9x_4 \amp + 6x_5 \amp = 15 </mrow>
</md>
we obtain the REF
<me> \begin{bmatrix} 3 \amp -9 \amp 12 \amp -9 \amp 6 \amp 15 \\ 0 \amp 2 \amp -4 \amp 4 \amp 2 \amp -6 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp 4 \end{bmatrix}
</me> 
Is this system consistent?  If so, identify any free variables and state the number of solutions. 
  </p>
</li> 

<li>
  <p>
Let <m>\displaystyle A = \left[ \begin{array}{cc}1 &#x26; 2 \\ 3 &#x26; 1 \\ 0 &#x26; 5\end{array} \right]</m> and <m>\displaystyle{\mathbf{b}}= \left[ \begin{array}{c}8 \\ 3 \\ 17\end{array} \right]</m>.
We determine whether <m>{\mathbf{b}}</m> is in the plane spanned by the columns of <m>A</m>. 
