<exercises xml:id="exercises-section43">
  <title>Exercises</title>

<exercise xml:id="elim-mcq-1">
  <title>Meaning of an Elementary Row Operation</title>

  <statement>
    <p>
      Which of the following <em>is</em> an elementary row operation used in elimination?
    </p>
  </statement>

  <choices randomize="yes">

    <choice correct="yes">
      <statement><p>Replacing a row by that row plus a multiple of another row.</p></statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          Correct — this is one of the three fundamental row operations.
        </p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p>Multiplying two rows together.</p></statement>
      <feedback><p>No — row multiplication is not allowed.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p>Raising a row to a power.</p></statement>
      <feedback><p>No — this has nothing to do with row operations.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

  </choices>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="elim-mcq-2">
  <title>First Step of Elimination</title>

  <statement>
    <p>
      Consider the system represented by the augmented matrix
      <me>
        \left[\begin{array}{cc|c}
        2 \amp 1 \amp 5\\
        4 \amp -2 \amp 6
        \end{array}\right].
      </me>
      What is a valid first elimination step?
    </p>
  </statement>

  <choices randomize="yes">

    <choice correct="yes">
      <statement><p>Replace Row 2 with Row 2 − 2·Row 1.</p></statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          Correct — this eliminates the <m>4</m> beneath the leading <m>2</m>.
        </p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p>Replace Row 1 with Row 1 × Row 2.</p></statement>
      <feedback><p>No — rows may not be multiplied together.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p>Replace Row 1 with Row 1 + Row 1.</p></statement>
      <feedback><p>No — that does not help eliminate any entry.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

  </choices>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="elim-mcq-3">
  <title>Pivot Identification</title>

  <statement>
    <p>
      In the row‑echelon matrix
      <me>
        \begin{bmatrix}
        1 \amp 3 \amp 2\\
        0 \amp 1 \amp -5\\
        0 \amp 0 \amp 7
        \end{bmatrix},
      </me>
      where are the pivots located?
    </p>
  </statement>

  <choices randomize="yes">

    <choice correct="yes">
      <statement><p>The entries 1, 1, and 7 on the diagonal.</p></statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          Correct — these are the first nonzero entries of each row.
        </p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p>The entries 3, 1, and −5.</p></statement>
      <feedback><p>No — those are not the first nonzero entries of their rows.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p>The entries 2, −5, and 7.</p></statement>
      <feedback><p>No — not all of these are pivots.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

  </choices>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="elim-mcq-4">
  <title>Meaning of a Row Swap</title>

  <statement>
    <p>
      Why might one perform a row swap during elimination?
    </p>
  </statement>

  <choices randomize="yes">

    <choice correct="yes">
      <statement><p>To move a nonzero entry into a pivot position.</p></statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          Correct — swapping helps ensure each pivot is nonzero.
        </p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p>To change the solution set of the system.</p></statement>
      <feedback><p>No — row operations must preserve the solution set.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p>To make the matrix symmetric.</p></statement>
      <feedback><p>No — symmetry is not relevant to elimination.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

  </choices>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="elim-mcq-5">
  <title>Interpreting an Inconsistent System</title>

  <statement>
    <p>
      After performing elimination, you obtain the augmented row
      <me>
        \begin{bmatrix}0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp | \amp 5\end{bmatrix}.
      </me>
      What does this indicate?
    </p>
  </statement>

  <choices randomize="yes">

    <choice correct="yes">
      <statement><p>The system is inconsistent and has no solution.</p></statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          Correct — the equation <m>0=5</m> cannot be satisfied.
        </p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p>There are infinitely many solutions.</p></statement>
      <feedback><p>No — that would arise from a row of all zeros <em>including</em> the augmented entry.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p>There is exactly one solution.</p></statement>
      <feedback><p>No — contradiction rows mean no solution.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

  </choices>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="elim-mcq-6">
  <title>Back‑Substitution Step</title>

  <statement>
    <p>
      After elimination, a system is reduced to:
      <me>
        \begin{aligned}
          x + 2y \amp= 5,\\
          y \amp= 1.
        \end{aligned}
      </me>
      What is the value of <m>x</m>?
    </p>
  </statement>

  <choices randomize="yes">

    <choice correct="yes">
      <statement><p><m>x = 3</m></p></statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          Correct — substitute <m>y=1</m> into <m>x+2y=5</m>.
        </p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p><m>x = 2</m></p></statement>
      <feedback><p>No — substitution gives <m>x=5-2=3</m>.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p><m>x = -1</m></p></statement>
      <feedback><p>No — that would satisfy <m>x+2=5</m> incorrectly.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

  </choices>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="rank-mcq-1">
  <title>Meaning of Matrix Rank</title>

  <statement>
    <p>
      What is the rank of a matrix?
    </p>
  </statement>

  <choices randomize="yes">

    <choice correct="yes">
      <statement>
        <p>
          The number of pivot columns in its row‑echelon form.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          Correct — rank equals the number of leading 1s, which is also the dimension of the column space.
        </p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p>The number of nonzero rows before row reduction.</p></statement>
      <feedback><p>No — rank must be computed after row reduction, not before.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p>The number of columns of the matrix.</p></statement>
      <feedback><p>No — only pivot columns count.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

  </choices>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="rank-mcq-2">
  <title>Interpreting Span</title>

  <statement>
    <p>
      Let <m>\vec{v}_1, \vec{v}_2</m> be vectors in <m>\mathbb{R}^3</m>.  
      What does <m>\operatorname{span}\{\vec{v}_1,\vec{v}_2\}</m> represent?
    </p>
  </statement>

  <choices randomize="yes">

    <choice correct="yes">
      <statement><p>The set of all linear combinations of <m>\vec{v}_1</m> and <m>\vec{v}_2</m>.</p></statement>
      <feedback><p>Correct — span is defined as all linear combinations.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p>Only the vectors <m>\vec{v}_1</m> and <m>\vec{v}_2</m> themselves.</p></statement>
      <feedback><p>No — the span contains infinitely many vectors.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p>The set of all vectors perpendicular to <m>\vec{v}_1</m> and <m>\vec{v}_2</m>.</p></statement>
      <feedback><p>No — that describes the orthogonal complement, not the span.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

  </choices>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="rank-mcq-3">
  <title>Rank and Solutions</title>

  <statement>
    <p>
      For a system <m>A\vec{x}=\vec{b}</m>, when is the system consistent?
    </p>
  </statement>

  <choices randomize="yes">

    <choice correct="yes">
      <statement>
        <p>The system is consistent exactly when <m>\operatorname{rank}(A)=\operatorname{rank}([A\mid \vec{b}])</m>.</p>
      </statement>
      <feedback><p>Correct — equality of ranks is the standard consistency criterion.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p>When <m>A</m> has at least one pivot in every row.</p></statement>
      <feedback><p>No — what matters is comparing the two ranks, not pivot count alone.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p>When <m>\vec{b}=\vec{0}</m>.</p></statement>
      <feedback><p>No — homogeneous systems are always consistent, but this is not the general criterion.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

  </choices>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="a3-elem-row-ops">
  <statement>
    <p>List the three <em>elementary row operations</em>. What do these row operations preserve?</p>
  </statement>

  <solution>
    <p>The three elementary row operations are:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Swap two rows.</li>
      <li>Multiply a row by a nonzero scalar.</li>
      <li>Replace a row by itself plus a multiple of another row.</li>
    </ul>

    <p>
      These operations <em>preserve the solution set</em> of the linear system.  
      That is, performing any sequence of these operations does not change the set of solutions.
    </p>
  </solution>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="a3-free-variable">
  <statement>
    <p>If a linear system has a <em>free variable</em>, what does that tell you about the solution space?</p>
  </statement>

  <solution>
    <p>
      A free variable means the system has <em>infinitely many solutions</em>.  
      Free variables correspond to directions in which the solution can vary, giving a solution space
      that forms a line, plane, or higher-dimensional affine subset.
    </p>
  </solution>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="a3-consistency-1">
  <statement>
    <p>Is this system consistent? If so, why? If not, why not?</p>

    <md>
      <mrow> x_1 - 2x_2 + x_3 \amp = 0 </mrow>
      <mrow> 2x_2 - 8x_3 \amp = 8 </mrow>
      <mrow> -4x_1 + 5x_2 + 9x_3 \amp = -9 </mrow>
    </md>

    <p>This system reduces to:</p>

    <md>
      <mrow> x_1 - 2x_2 + x_3 \amp = 0 </mrow>
      <mrow> x_2 - 4x_3 \amp = 4 </mrow>
      <mrow> x_3 \amp = 3 </mrow>
    </md>

    <p>The augmented matrix is:</p>

    <me>
      \left[
      \begin{array}{ccc|c}
        1 \amp -2 \amp 1 \amp 0\\
        0 \amp 1 \amp -4 \amp 4\\
        0 \amp 0 \amp 3 \amp 3
      \end{array}
      \right]
    </me>
  </statement>

  <solution>
    <p>
      The system is <strong>consistent</strong> because no row reduces to a contradiction of the form  
      <m>[0\ 0\ 0\ |\ c]</m> with <m>c\neq 0</m>.  
      The last equation <m>3x_3 = 3</m> is solvable (<m>x_3 = 1</m>), and the others follow.
    </p>
  </solution>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="a3-consistency-2">
  <statement>
    <p>Determine if the system is consistent. If so, why? If not, why not?</p>

    <md>
      <mrow>3x_2 - 6x_3 \amp = 8 </mrow>
      <mrow> x_1 - 2x_2 + 3x_3 \amp = -1 </mrow>
      <mrow> 5x_1 - 7x_2 + 9x_3 \amp = 0 </mrow>
    </md>

    <p>Row reduction gives:</p>

    <md>
      <mrow> \left[
      \begin{array}{ccc|c}
        0 \amp 3 \amp -6 \amp 8\\
        1 \amp -2 \amp 3 \amp -1\\
        5 \amp -7 \amp 9 \amp 0
      \end{array}
      \right]
      \amp \sim
      \left[
      \begin{array}{ccc|c}
        1 \amp -2 \amp 3 \amp -1\\
        0 \amp 3 \amp -6 \amp 8\\
        0 \amp 3 \amp -6 \amp 5
      \end{array}
      \right] </mrow>
      <mrow> \amp \sim
      \left[
      \begin{array}{ccc|c}
        1 \amp -2 \amp 3 \amp -1\\
        0 \amp 3 \amp -6 \amp 8\\
        0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp -3
      \end{array}
      \right] </mrow>
    </md>
  </statement>

  <solution>
    <p>
      The last row corresponds to <m>0 = -3</m>, a contradiction.  
      Therefore, the system is <strong>inconsistent</strong> and has <em>no solution</em>.
    </p>
  </solution>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="span-plane-a">
  <statement>
    <p>
      Let 
      <m>A=\begin{bmatrix}1 \amp 2\\[4pt] 3 \amp 1\\[4pt] 0 \amp 5\end{bmatrix}</m> 
      and 
      <m>\vec{b}=\begin{bmatrix}8\\3\\17\end{bmatrix}</m>.
      We want to determine whether <m>\vec{b}</m> lies in the plane spanned by the columns of <m>A</m>.
    </p>

    <ol>
      <li>
        <p>
          Finish rewriting this question in vector form:  
          “Do weights <m>x_1</m> and <m>x_2</m> exist so that …?”
        </p>
      </li>

      <li>
        <p>
          The augmented matrix row‑reduces as follows:
        </p>

        <md>
          <mrow> \left[
          \begin{array}{cc|c}
            1 \amp 2 \amp 8\\
            3 \amp 1 \amp 3\\
            0 \amp 5 \amp 17
          \end{array}
          \right]
          \amp \sim
          \left[
          \begin{array}{cc|c}
            1 \amp 2 \amp 8\\
            0 \amp -5 \amp -21\\
            0 \amp 5 \amp 17
          \end{array}
          \right] </mrow>
          <mrow> \amp \sim
          \left[
          \begin{array}{cc|c}
            1 \amp 2 \amp 8\\
            0 \amp -5 \amp -21\\
            0 \amp 0 \amp -4
          \end{array}
          \right]. </mrow>
        </md>

        <p>
          Is <m>\vec{b}</m> in the plane spanned by the columns of <m>A</m>?
        </p>
      </li>
    </ol>
  </statement>

  <solution>
    <p><strong>(a)</strong> The vector‑form question is:</p>

    <me>
      \text{Do there exist }x_1,x_2\text{ such that }
      x_1\begin{bmatrix}1\\3\\0\end{bmatrix}
      +
      x_2\begin{bmatrix}2\\1\\5\end{bmatrix}
      =
      \begin{bmatrix}8\\3\\17\end{bmatrix} ?
    </me>

    <p><strong>(b)</strong> The final row of the REF matrix is:</p>

    <me>
      \left[0\ \ 0\ \ |\ -4\right],
    </me>

    <p>
      which corresponds to the equation <m>0=-4</m>, a contradiction.  
      Therefore the system has **no solution**, and
    </p>

    <me>
      \vec{b} \text{ is NOT in } \operatorname{span}\{ \text{columns of }A\}.
    </me>
  </solution>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="aug-to-system">
  <statement>
    <p>
      Consider the augmented matrix:
    </p>

    <me>
      \left[
      \begin{array}{ccc|c}
        2 \amp 3 \amp 4 \amp 9\\
        -3 \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp -2
      \end{array}
      \right].
    </me>

    <ol marker="(a)">
      <li><p>Write the corresponding system of equations.</p></li>

      <li>
        <p>
          Fill in the missing coefficients in the vector equation:
        </p>

        <me>
          x_1\begin{bmatrix}2\\-3\end{bmatrix}
          \;+\;
          x_2\begin{bmatrix}3\\1\end{bmatrix}
          \;+\;
          x_3\begin{bmatrix}4\\0\end{bmatrix}
          \;=\;
          \begin{bmatrix}9\\-2\end{bmatrix}.
        </me>
      </li>

      <li><p>Write this in the form <m>A\vec{x}=\vec{b}</m>.</p></li>
    </ol>
  </statement>

  <solution>
    <p><strong>(a) System of equations:</strong></p>

    <md>
      <mrow>2x_1 + 3x_2 + 4x_3 \amp = 9</mrow>
      <mrow>-3x_1 + 1x_2 + 0x_3 \amp = -2</mrow>
    </md>

    <p><strong>(b)</strong> The completed vector equation already appears correct (no blanks remain).</p>

    <p><strong>(c) Matrix equation:</strong></p>

    <me>
      \begin{bmatrix}
        2 \amp 3 \amp 4\\
        -3 \amp 1 \amp 0
      \end{bmatrix}
      \begin{bmatrix}
        x_1\\x_2\\x_3
      \end{bmatrix}
      =
      \begin{bmatrix}
        9\\-2
      \end{bmatrix}.
    </me>
  </solution>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="span-fillins">
  <statement>
    <p>
      The equation <m>A\vec{x}=\vec{b}</m> has a solution if and only if <m>\vec{b}</m> is a
      <fillin characters="10"/> <fillin characters="10"/> 
      of the columns of <m>A</m>.
    </p>
  </statement>

  <solution>
    <p>
      The correct phrase is:
    </p>

    <me>
      \vec{b}\text{ is a linear combination of the columns of }A.
    </me>

    <p>Thus the filled‑in blanks are: <strong>linear</strong> and <strong>combination</strong>.</p>
  </solution>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="inverse-solve-2x2">
  <statement>
    <p>
      Use the inverse of 
      <m>
        A=\begin{bmatrix}-7 \amp 3\\ 5 \amp -2\end{bmatrix}
      </m>
      to solve:
    </p>

    <md>
      <mrow> -7x_1 + 3x_2 \amp = 2 </mrow>
      <mrow> 5x_1 - 2x_2 \amp = 1 </mrow>
    </md>
  </statement>

  <solution>
    <p><strong>1. Compute the inverse.</strong></p>

    <p>
      For 
      <m>A=\begin{bmatrix}a \amp b\\ c \amp d\end{bmatrix}</m>,
      <m>A^{-1} = \frac{1}{ad-bc}\begin{bmatrix}d \amp -b\\ -c \amp a\end{bmatrix}</m>.
    </p>

    <p>
      Here <m>a=-7</m>, <m>b=3</m>, <m>c=5</m>, <m>d=-2</m>.
    </p>

    <me>
      ad-bc = (-7)(-2) - (3)(5) = 14 - 15 = -1.
    </me>

    <me>
      A^{-1}
      =
      -1^{-1}
      \begin{bmatrix}
        -2 \amp -3\\
        -5 \amp -7
      \end{bmatrix}
      =
      \begin{bmatrix}
        2 \amp 3\\
        5 \amp 7
      \end{bmatrix}.
    </me>

    <p><strong>2. Compute <m>\vec{x}=A^{-1}\vec{b}</m>.</strong></p>

    <me>
      \vec{b}=\begin{bmatrix}2\\1\end{bmatrix},
      \qquad
      \vec{x}
      =
      \begin{bmatrix}
        2 \amp 3\\
        5 \amp 7
      \end{bmatrix}
      \begin{bmatrix}
        2\\1
      \end{bmatrix}
      =
      \begin{bmatrix}
        2\cdot 2 + 3\cdot 1\\
        5\cdot 2 + 7\cdot 1
      \end{bmatrix}
      =
      \begin{bmatrix}
        7\\17
      \end{bmatrix}.
    </me>

    <p>
      Thus the solution is 
      <m>x_1=7,\; x_2=17</m>.
    </p>
  </solution>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="inverse-3x3">
  <statement>
    <p>
      Use the augmented matrix below to determine the inverse of
      <m>A=\begin{bmatrix}2 \amp 0 \amp 0\\ -3 \amp 0 \amp 1\\ 0 \amp 1 \amp 0\end{bmatrix}</m>, 
      if it exists.
    </p>

    <me>
      \left[
      \begin{array}{ccc|ccc}
        2 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp 0\\
        -3 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp 0\\
        0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 1
      \end{array}
      \right]
      \sim \dots \sim
      \left[
      \begin{array}{ccc|ccc}
        1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp \tfrac12 \amp 0 \amp 0\\
        0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 1\\
        0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp \tfrac12 \amp 1 \amp 0
      \end{array}
      \right]
    </me>
  </statement>

  <solution>
    <p>
      The final augmented matrix has the form <m>[I\mid A^{-1}]</m>.  
      Therefore:
    </p>

    <me>
      A^{-1}
      =
      \begin{bmatrix}
        \tfrac12 \amp 0 \amp 0\\
        0 \amp 0 \amp 1\\
        \tfrac12 \amp 1 \amp 0
      \end{bmatrix}.
    </me>

    <p>Since we completed the reduction successfully, <m>A</m> is invertible.</p>
  </solution>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="rank-open-1">
  <statement>
    <p>
      Compute the rank of  
      <m>
      A=\begin{bmatrix}
      1 \amp 2 \amp 3\\
      2 \amp 4 \amp 6\\
      1 \amp 1 \amp 0
      \end{bmatrix}
      </m>.
      Then describe <m>\operatorname{span}\{\text{columns of }A\}</m>.
    </p>
  </statement>

  <solution>
    <p>
      Row‑reduce:
    </p>

    <md>
      <mrow> \begin{bmatrix}
      1 \amp 2 \amp 3\\
      2 \amp 4 \amp 6\\
      1 \amp 1 \amp 0
      \end{bmatrix}
      \amp \sim
      \begin{bmatrix}
      1 \amp 2 \amp 3\\
      0 \amp 0 \amp 0\\
      0 \amp -1 \amp -3
      \end{bmatrix} </mrow>
      <mrow> \amp \sim
      \begin{bmatrix}
      1 \amp 2 \amp 3\\
      0 \amp 1 \amp 3\\
      0 \amp 0 \amp 0
      \end{bmatrix}. </mrow>
    </md>

    <p>
      There are 2 pivot columns, so
      <m>\operatorname{rank}(A)=2</m>.
    </p>

    <p>
      Thus the columns of <m>A</m> span a <strong>2‑dimensional plane</strong> in <m>\mathbb{R}^3</m>.
    </p>
  </solution>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="rank-open-2">
  <statement>
    <p>
      Let  
      <m>\vec{u}=\begin{bmatrix}1\\2\\1\end{bmatrix}</m>,  
      <m>\vec{v}=\begin{bmatrix}-1\\1\\0\end{bmatrix}</m>,  
      and  
      <m>\vec{w}=\begin{bmatrix}3\\3\\2\end{bmatrix}</m>.  
      Determine whether <m>\vec{w}</m> is in <m>\operatorname{span}\{\vec{u},\vec{v}\}</m>.
    </p>
  </statement>

  <solution>
    <p>
      Solve <m>a\vec{u} + b\vec{v} = \vec{w}</m>:
    </p>

    <me>
      a\begin{bmatrix}1\\2\\1\end{bmatrix}
      + b\begin{bmatrix}-1\\1\\0\end{bmatrix}
      =
      \begin{bmatrix}3\\3\\2\end{bmatrix}.
    </me>

    <p>Component equations:</p>

    <md>
      <mrow>a - b \amp = 3</mrow>
      <mrow>2a + b \amp = 3</mrow>
      <mrow>a \amp = 2</mrow>
    </md>

    <p>
      From the third equation, <m>a=2</m>.  
      Substitute into the first: <m>2 - b = 3</m> → <m>b=-1</m>.  
      Check the second:
    </p>

    <me>
      2(2) + (-1) = 3 \quad \text{✓}
    </me>

    <p>
      Therefore
      <m>\vec{w} = 2\vec{u} - \vec{v}</m>,
      so <m>\vec{w}</m> <strong>is</strong> in the span.
    </p>
  </solution>
</exercise>

</exercises>

</section>

      <section xml:id="sec-Advancedlearningobjectives43">
        <title>Advanced learning objectives</title>

        <p>
          In addition to mastering the basic objectives, here are the tasks you should be able 
          to perform, with practice:
        </p>

        <ul>
          <li>
<p>
  Use elimination logically and systematically to reduce a system to a form
  where one can read off variables, such as reaching an equation like
  <m>x_{3} = 2</m>.
</p>
          </li>

          <li>
<p>
  Explain how elimination is connected to finding matrix inverses by solving
  multiple systems <m>A\vec{x}=\vec{b}</m> for different right-hand sides.
</p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
<p>
  Analyze how elimination applies even when <m>A</m> is non-invertible or
  non-square, and interpret what this implies about the possible solution
  sets of the system.
</p>
            </p>
          </li>

        </ul>

      </section>


</handout>